% parrot0 INTENT PHRASES — multi-word recall/command idioms as KNOWLEDGE, not C arrays.
%
% Cardinal principle (PRINCIPLES.md, the KB-migration direction made general):
%   a FIXED engine matches; the KB learns. gen193 put closed-class WORDS in the KB
%   (conjunction/1, stopword/1, social_marker/2) so the class grows at runtime with no
%   code edit. gen211 extends the SAME law to multi-word INTENT phrases: the exact
%   surface forms that mean "ask my name", "ask the time", etc. are facts here, queried
%   by kb_intent_match() in the C kernel. Teaching parrot0 a new form at runtime
%   ("learn \"how do you call me\" as asking my name") asserts another intent_phrase/2
%   into the SESSION layer and the very same matcher fires — no new handler, no rebuild.
%
% Representation: intent_phrase(IntentName, "surface form"). The surface form is a
% quoted, already-normalized (lowercase) atom so spaces and a trailing '?' are content,
% not separators (kb.c parse_term keeps the quotes; the matcher strips them).
%
% Loaded as KB_BASE at brain_create, so these curated forms never land in a session
% save, while a runtime-taught form (KB_SESSION) does persist on /save.

% --- ask_name: "what is my name?" and its fixed variants (EN + IT) ---
% Italian recall idiom — the read-side mirror of "mi chiamo X"; the fixed form of
% "what's my name?", so it belongs in the same lexicon, not a new handler.

% intent_cue(Intent, "fragment") — SUBSTRING cues (matched by kb_cue_match, i.e. the
% fragment may appear anywhere in the turn), as opposed to intent_phrase/2 which is the
% WHOLE normalized turn (exact). Same KB-first law: the cue set grows at runtime.

% --- brevity: the user asking for short / non-verbose answers (EN + IT) ---

% --- gen223: pi-agent read-only verbs (mod_piact, docs/use-on-pi-agent.md). The phrasings
% an OpenAI-style client uses to name each tool live HERE, not as chained cue("…") in C
% (that was a phrasebook — PRINCIPLES.md's impostor shape). kb_cue_match queries these; a
% new phrasing is DATA, teachable at runtime, no recompile. Structural anchors (leading
% "read "/"grep "/"ls" prefix, "find"+"named" AND-logic) stay in C as shape, not vocabulary.

% --- gen227 (basic-chat cat.104): AI/ML identity probes (EN + IT). Answered
% HONESTLY from the self-model by mod_self: parrot0 is a from-scratch C program
% with no LLM at runtime. Cues are anchored on "are you …"/"your …" so a generic
% knowledge question ("what is a neural network") is NOT hijacked. ---




% --- gen229 (LLMSCORE behavioural resemblance): embodiment / daily-life probes.
% NOT identity questions (those are off-limits in LLMSCORE); these ask about a
% BODY parrot0 doesn't have, and the honest reply ("I don't eat or sleep") is the
% same one an LLM gives. Engages instead of walling; states a truth, claims no
% identity. Cues anchored on eating/sleeping/tiredness so they don't over-fire. ---

% --- gen241 (LLMSCORE-check): location/weather-of-self probes. parrot0 has no body
% or place, so it can't feel weather; the honest answer engages, it doesn't wall.

% --- gen231 (LLMSCORE): opinion / preference probes ("what's your favorite thing
% to do on a rainy day", "do you enjoy music"). parrot0 has no personal tastes or
% lived experience; the honest answer engages instead of walling and is the same an
% LLM gives. Anchored on "your favorite/favourite" and "do you like/enjoy/prefer". ---
% gen333 (LLMSCORE): recent-interest questions use the English second-person
% present-perfect frame. Keep the INTERROGATIVE anchor in every cue: a statement
% such as "I'm glad you've been enjoying the books" is about the user and must
% not be stolen by the self-preference handler.

% --- gen333 (LLMSCORE counterexamples): surface vocabulary for fixed engines. ---
% These are deliberately intent_cue facts even when the words look like parser
% punctuation. C owns ordering, binding and computation; the KB owns which forms
% mean "count", "range endpoint", "initial", or "relationship". keyword/1 asks
% the shared evidence scorer for token boundaries instead of substring guesses.

% Computed number-property counts over bounded ranges.
% intent_family/2 is the trainer-visible consumer contract: these hypotheses
% cooperate inside one faculty and therefore must not be read as mutually
% exclusive global intents. autolearn queries each component through the shared
% input.classify scorer and can teach the one Gap while leaving mechanics in C.

% A frame maps an open-cue class to its compatible close-cue class. Adding a
% cue to either class changes the parser live; adding a new pair needs one
% range_frame/2 fact, not a branch in C.

% Quoted per-word initial projection and the nearby anagram intent. Keeping both
% in the KB lets the engine distinguish "letters of ... form" from the more
% specific initials+scope request without deleting a working anagram surface.

% Explicit no-overlap propositions and their two question shapes.

% --- gen228 (basic-chat cat.86): "would you rather" opener (the bare "A or B"
% choice itself is recognized structurally in mod_chitchat, not listed here). ---

% =========================================================================
% gen214: the LEARNABLE registry — what can be taught at runtime, as DATA.
%
% learnable(Label, Intent, Mode). ONE generic handler (try_teach_form) reads this: on a
% turn that carries a teach verb ("learn/teach/use/impara/…") and a quoted span, it finds
% the Label that occurs in the turn and asserts the right fact for that Intent:
%   exact     -> intent_phrase(Intent, "form")      (whole-turn recognition)
%   substring -> intent_cue(Intent, "fragment")     (substring recognition)
%   fill      -> response_template(Intent, "text")  (an OUTPUT phrasing; {name} slot)
% So adding a learnable intent is now DATA (a learnable/3 row + its base forms), not C —
% the per-intent teach handlers are gone. Label is matched against the raw (non-canonical)
% turn, so natural EN+IT labels both route. Mode picks the predicate AND the span source
% (exact/substring store the normalized span; fill keeps the raw casing for {name}).
% gen272 (Track 5.5, the runtime-growth demo): the teach-verb class ITSELF is
% learnable. gen271 migrated the guard of try_teach_form to KB
% (intent_cue(00_lex_chain332, …)), so "learn \"memorizza \" as a teaching
% verb" asserts a new verb into the very vocabulary that gates teaching — a
% previously deaf branch hooks with no rebuild, and the new verb can then
% teach anything else the registry knows. Reflexive growth as pure DATA.

% gen335 (KB-first research responses): teachable response phrasings.
% Each intent has an EN+IT label so the user can say "insegnami a <label> con <new text>"
% and the new phrasing joins the rotation; on /save it persists in the session KB.

% gen335 (proper names): teachable exceptions from translation.
% "non tradurre luna" adds proper_name(luna) — the canonicalizer skips tr/2 for it.

% --- gen240 (universal-comprehension, social branch): smalltalk CONTINUITY. A
% conversational/experiential turn (first-person experience or opinion, or a
% question turned back to parrot0) is COMPREHENSIBLE even with no fact to fetch:
% the honest move is to keep the thread alive (acknowledge + ask back), never a
% blind wall. These social markers are the cue; mod_smalltalk is the last-resort
% continuity catch (registered after learn). EN + IT, the lexicon grows here. ---

% gen240: broader smalltalk cues (multi-word social phrases, safe as substrings).
% Italian conversational phrases

% --- gen257: OR-chain perception (Track 5.1, outer-circle codebase work). The
% trigger vocabulary for "how many or-chains of calls to <fn> in <path>?" lives
% HERE from day one — this very feature about C phrasebooks must not be one. A
% new phrasing is DATA, teachable at runtime via the generic learnable/3 path,
% no recompile. The function name and path are structural anchors parsed in C
% (shape, not vocabulary).

% --- gen258: plan requests (Track 5.2). "make a plan to <goal>" — the trigger
% surface is knowledge; the goal itself is recognized from goal_cue/2 facts in
% the plan-action domain (kb/experts/codebase/actions.p0) and the steps are
% DERIVED by the generic backward chainer, never a hardcoded pipeline.

% --- gen259: execute a derived plan through KB action_impl/2 bindings. These
% cues only ask parrot0 to WALK the plan it can already derive; the domain stays
% in kb/experts/codebase/actions.p0 and missing implementations are named as the
% next pull instead of fabricated.

% --- gen265 (the first RULESCORE pull): a rules-spec implementation request is
% a CATEGORY. The FORM (>=2 ordered numbered rule markers, paragraph length) is
% structural C in mod_rulespec; the VOCABULARY that names the request and the
% rule CLASSES lives here — teach a cue, the category widens with no rebuild.
% First honest step: recognize the spec, report what was understood (title,
% rule count, rule classes) and decline the translation naming the F4 gap; a
% chitchat/pragma misclaim is worse than a wall (gen254).

% rule classes (word classes, KB-first): which kinds of rules a spec states

% gen266: rule sub-classes used to EXTRACT count_to_threshold parameters from a
% recognized spec (all vocabulary, teachable at runtime): the rule that GAINS
% names the scoring token (the word after an input verb), the rule that REACHES
% names the threshold, the print cue names the final word.

% --- gen267 (universal-comprehension §2/§4.2, first slice): the request/
% generate FORM. The schema "[V-imp] [NP] (in <lang>)" is structural C in
% mod_reqgen (a LATE module: it only catches turns every other module already
% declined); the imperative-verb class and the language names live here. The
% payoff is the doc's informed decline: the blind wall becomes "I understood
% the request — produce X — but ..." with the gap named. Matched as WHOLE
% tokens, not substrings.

% gen270 (universal-comprehension §8, produce-artifact): the FILE-artifact
% request. "file" is the artifact word (same token EN/IT); the name markers
% introduce the filename ("a file NAMED pupo.txt" / "un file CHIAMATO
% pupo.txt"). Whole-token matched in mod_reqgen; the action itself is gated by
% artifact_shape(empty_file, …) in the programming KB.

% gen271 (Track 5.4, coding-agent-evolution): the FIRST real cue-chain site
% migrated out of C by parrot0's own derived kbfirst_migration plan — these
% eight facts were EMITTED by emit_facts from the OR-chain that guarded
% try_teach_form (src/brain/00-lex.c, chain at the then-line 332), and the
% chain is now ONE kb_cue_match(b, "00_lex_chain332", low) call. The teach-verb
% vocabulary itself became taught knowledge: a new verb is a fact here (or a
% runtime assert), never a recompile. Trailing spaces are content (the verbs
% must end the word: "use " must not fire on "user").

% gen273 (Track 5.4, second real migration — by whole module): the two
% counterfactual chains of src/brain/85-translate-synth-world.c
% (mod_counterfactual's else_form and question_shape), emitted by the derived
% plan and applied by the external loop. Counter: 340 -> 338.

% gen274 (Track 5.4, third real migration — with per-chain applicability): five
% of the six cue chains of src/brain/65-induce-verify-shell.c (mod_summary's
% want_sum/want_gist/focus_intent, mod_discourse's summary trigger,
% is_mixed_turn's thanks-corrective cues), emitted by the derived plan and
% applied by the external loop. The sixth chain (is_wellbeing_content, line 770
% at emit time) was SKIPPED honestly by the plan itself: the kb_cue_match call
% shape imports `b`, which that helper never sees — its facts are therefore NOT
% committed (unused knowledge would be a lie about what the code reads).
% Counter: 338 -> 333.

% gen275 (Track 5.4, fourth real migration — by whole module): all 16 cue
% chains of src/brain/50-self-research-loop.c (mod_loop's self-challenge
% triggers and the identity/existence/capability gates), emitted by the
% derived plan and applied by the external loop; every chain had `b` in
% scope, zero skips. NB on chain439: input is canonicalized before matching,
% so Italian "chi sei" arrives as "who sei" — that cue is correct, not a
% typo (it was a code comment at the old site). Counter: 333 -> 317.

% M1 (deep-reasoning §4bis): the provenance query — "where did you learn about X?"
% / "what is your source for X?" (IT "dove hai imparato" / "qual è la tua fonte"
% -> canonicalized "your source"). KB-first cue set, teachable like the migrated
% chains; keeps the cuechains ratchet from rising.

% deep-reasoning M3 (docs/plans/deep-reasoning.md §5): the trigger that starts the
% budgeted multi-hop inference loop on a yes/no question. KB-first, teachable.
% deep-reasoning M3: the Italian deep-trigger cues, so the report is localized
% (kb_cue_match, not a C cue chain — keeps the cuechains ratchet at 317).

% --- gen323 (TODO.md P1, the code KEYHOLE) ------------------------------------
% The code faculties were REAL (25/25 code-bench gates) but reachable only
% through an exact C phrasebook: `cue(s,"explain this code")` answered, while
% "explain what this does:" — the same faculty, the same snippet, one phrasing
% away — hit the wall "That looks like a snippet of code.". A coding agent whose
% analysis is reachable only by the magic words cannot receive a GitHub issue,
% which is the whole mission.
%
% This is the C-series law applied to code (gen51, gen193, gen211): a lexical
% class is KNOWLEDGE, not a C branch. mod_code now asks kb_cue_match, so the
% phrasing set grows AT RUNTIME — "call X a way of asking about code" widens the
% surface with no rebuild, and adding a phrasing costs a fact, not a generation.
%
% Widening the language surface is only safe because the REGISTER evidence was
% tightened in the same generation: mod_code declines when the section after the
% colon is not recognizably C or Python, so prose keeps its turn. (Before that
% guard, "what is wrong with this: the sky is blue" was answered with "I did not
% find obvious errors in this code snippet" — prose misclaimed as code.)

% qtype 1 — find the defect.

% qtype 2 — repair it.

% qtype 3 — which language.

% qtype 4 — is it valid.

% qtype 5 — explain it. These are the phrasings that walled in the 2026-07-12
% conversation with F.; each one is now a fact, not a C branch.

% --- gen325 (TODO.md P6, forge plan §18): WHERE I END ------------------------
% "what are you unable to do?" was claimed by the identity module ("I am
% parrot0."), and "cosa non sai fare?" got the CAPABILITY list — the question was
% inverted and the answer was still a brochure. The negative reading is the
% specific one, so mod_self tests these cues BEFORE identity and capability.
% The ANSWER is derived from capability/2 + capability_wall/2 (kb/core/
% capabilities.p0, generated from gate results) — no faculty name lives in C.

